    Root‑cause analysis                                                         
                                                                                
     1 What the stack tells us                                                  
        • The crash occurs inside parse_string() (frame 5) while it is copying  
          the characters of a JSON string literal.                              
        • The next relevant frame (7) shows the parsing of a value              
          (parse_value) that eventually calls parse_string.                     
        • The heap‑overflow message originates from the allocator when it       
          later frees the buffer that parse_string allocated.                   
     2 State of the program when the crash happens                              
        • The driver fed a single JSON token to the parser:  "\"abc (note the   
          missing closing \").                                                  
        • In parse_string() the loop starting at line 798 repeatedly reads      
          *input_end until it finds a terminating quote.                        
        • There is no explicit guard that guarantees input_end still points     
          inside the allocated input buffer before the loop condition is        
          evaluated.                                                            
        • When the input is unterminated, the loop keeps advancing input_end    
          until it passes the end of the buffer. At that point *input_end       
          accesses memory beyond the original buffer, and later the function    
          computes                                                              
                                                                                
           allocation_length = (size_t)(input_end -                             
           buffer_at_offset(input_buffer)) - skipped_bytes;                     
                                                                                
          which can become a huge (wrapped) value. The subsequent allocation    
          and the copy loop then write past the heap region that the allocator  
          handed out, leading the heap checker to abort with Heap buffer        
          overflow.                                                             
     3 Where the defect lives                                                   
        • The missing bounds check in the “read‑until‑quote” loop (lines        
          798‑812).                                                             
        • The existing guard for a trailing backslash (if ((size_t)(input_end   
          + 1 - input_buffer->content) >= input_buffer->length)) only protects  
          against a final backslash, not against a missing quote.               
     4 Why the bug is exploitable with the supplied input                       
        • Input "abc is a syntactically incomplete string.                      
        • The parser never sees a closing quote, so input_end walks off the     
          end of input_buffer->content.                                         
        • Because input_end no longer points inside the original buffer, the    
          calculations of allocation_length and the subsequent copy into the    
          newly allocated output buffer operate on an incorrect size.           
        • The copy writes more bytes than the allocated heap block actually     
          contains → heap‑buffer‑overflow → abort.                              
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Proposed fixes                                                              
                                                                                
    1. Minimal local fix (patch the immediate loop)                             
                                                                                
                                                                                
     /* --- original --- */                                                     
     while (*input_end != '\"')                                                 
     {                                                                          
         /* is escape sequence */                                               
         if (input_end[0] == '\\')                                              
         {                                                                      
             …                                                                  
         }                                                                      
         input_end++;                                                           
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
     /* --- patched --- */                                                      
     while (input_end < input_buffer->content + input_buffer->length &&         
     *input_end != '\"')                                                        
     {                                                                          
         /* is escape sequence */                                               
         if (input_end[0] == '\\')                                              
         {                                                                      
             …                                                                  
         }                                                                      
         input_end++;                                                           
     }                                                                          
     if (input_end >= input_buffer->content + input_buffer->length) {           
         /* unterminated string – report parse error */                         
         goto fail;                                                             
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    What this does:                                                             
                                                                                
     • Guarantees that we never dereference *input_end outside the allocated    
       buffer.                                                                  
     • As soon as we reach the physical end of the buffer we break out and go   
       to fail, which forwards the parser to the normal error‑handling path.    
     • The allocation size therefore never becomes nonsensical.                 
                                                                                
    2. More thorough root‑cause fix (defensive string parsing)                  
                                                                                
    The deeper problem is that parse_string trusts the approximation of the     
    string length (allocation_length) to allocate a buffer, and later copies    
    characters until it finds a quote without confirming that the source        
    buffer actually contains that many characters. A robust implementation      
    should:                                                                     
                                                                                
     1 Validate length up‑front – before entering the copy loop, confirm that   
       enough bytes remain to hold the entire quoted string, including escaped  
       characters.                                                              
     2 Never allocate based on extrapolated pointers – compute the allocation   
       size only after the entire string has been validated as terminating      
       within the buffer.                                                       
     3 Provide a clear error for malformed JSON rather than attempting to       
       allocate a large buffer and copy beyond its limits.                      
                                                                                
    A more complete redesign of parse_string could look like:                   
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static const unsigned char *parse_string(const unsigned char *const        
     buffer,                                                                    
                                              size_t buffer_length,             
                                              unsigned char **out)              
     {                                                                          
         const unsigned char *input_end = buffer + buffer_length;               
         const unsigned char *p = buffer;                                       
         size_t needed = 0;                                                     
                                                                                
         /* Quick check: we need at least the opening quote */                  
         if (p >= input_end || *p != '\"') goto fail;                           
         p++;   // skip opening quote                                           
                                                                                
         while (p < input_end)                                                  
         {                                                                      
             unsigned char ch = *p;                                             
             if (ch == '\"')                                                    
             {                                                                  
                 /* closing quote found – we can compute the exact length */    
                 needed = (size_t)(p - buffer);   // length without the         
     closing quote                                                              
                 break;                                                         
             }                                                                  
             if (ch == '\\')                                                    
             {                                                                  
                 if (p + 1 >= input_end) goto fail;   // escaped char needs     
     next byte                                                                  
                 needed++;                              // count escaped char   
     as one output byte                                                         
                 p++;                                   // skip escape char     
             }                                                                  
             p++;                                                               
         }                                                                      
                                                                                
         /* If we fell out without finding the closing quote */                 
         if (p == input_end) goto fail;                                         
                                                                                
         /* Allocate exactly the needed space + terminating NUL */              
         *out = (unsigned char *)input_buffer->hooks.allocate(needed + 1);      
         if (!*out) goto fail;                                                  
                                                                                
         /* Copy the characters (minus the opening quote) */                    
         unsigned char *q = *out;                                               
         p = buffer + 1;          // start after opening quote                  
         while (p < input_end && *p != '\"')                                    
         {                                                                      
             if (*p == '\\')                                                    
             {                                                                  
                 /* handle escape sequences … */                                
                 ++p;                                                           
             }                                                                  
             *q++ = *p++;                                                       
         }                                                                      
         *q = '\0';               // null‑terminate                             
                                                                                
         return *out;                                                           
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Why this is safer                                                           
                                                                                
     • The loop is bounded by the known input_end pointer, so it can never run  
       past the supplied buffer.                                                
     • needed is computed after the closing quote has been observed,            
       guaranteeing that the allocated size matches the real number of          
       characters that will be copied.                                          
     • Any malformed input results in an early goto fail, causing the parser    
       to treat the JSON as invalid rather than crashing.                       
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    3. Error‑handling improvement (recommended for production)                  
                                                                                
    Instead of silently propagating a parse error, the driver                   
    (bench_driver.c:19) should:                                                 
                                                                                
                                                                                
     cJSON *root = cJSON_ParseWithJsDoc(input_string);                          
     if (root == NULL) {                                                        
         fprintf(stderr, "JSON parse error at line %d: %s\n",                   
                 cJSON_GetErrorPosition()? cJSON_GetErrorPosition()->line :     
     -1,                                                                        
                 cJSON.GetErrorMsg());                                          
         return;                                                                
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Adding proper error reporting lets a developer see “unexpected end of JSON  
    input” rather than being surprised by a heap overflow.                      
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Summary (minimal vs. thorough)                                              
                                                                                
                                                                                
     Fix style  Change scope                   Effect                           
     ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────   
     Minimal    Add a bounds check and         Stops the loop as soon as the    
                early‑exit in the              buffer ends; no out‑of‑bounds    
                quote‑search loop.             allocation.                      
     Thorough   Rewrite parse_string to        Guarantees correct allocation    
                validate length before         size, eliminates the             
                allocation and copy only       possibility of any               
                after a closing quote is       out‑of‑bounds heap write, and    
                found.                         provides a clean failure mode.   
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Recommendation👇                                                            
                                                                                
                                                                                
     ##### Recommendation                                                       
     1. Apply the minimal patch shown above to `cJSON.c` (add bounds check to   
